document where it no longer exerts an effect on non-floated items. Actually, this isn’t strictly true.

	<br/><br/>
	If a floated element is followed by an element in the flow of the document, the element’s box will
	behave as if the float didn’t exist. However, the textural content of the box retains some memory
	of the floated element and moves out of the way to make room. In technical terms, a line box next
	to a floated element is shortened to make room for the floated element, thereby flowing around
	the floated box. In fact, floats were created to allow text to flow around images (see Figure 3-16).
